  <discussion>Frequent in the western Canadian mountains on calcareous cliffs, Seligeria donniana is disjunct to Colorado, and in temperate eastern North America is found from Tennessee north to Newfoundland.  The tiny, stiff plants have stoutly subulate leaves with serrulate proximal portions, which are characteristic of this species.  The capsules are hemispheric, are relatively small, and have no peristome.</discussion>
